		        <div class="post-17425 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-foreign-policy category-japan-nuclear category-nuclear-weapon-2 tag-hiroshima" id="post-17425">    
    <div class="latest-posts-post">
                <a href="https://allthingsnuclear.org/gkulacki/hiroshima-and-harlem" class="post_thumbnail ">
            <span><img src='https://cdn.allthingsnuclear.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/matsubara-miyoko-property-of-hiroshima-peace-memorial-museum.jpg' /></span>
        </a>

        <div class="post_details_inner">
            <h1>
                <a href="https://allthingsnuclear.org/gkulacki/hiroshima-and-harlem" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to What’s the Connection Between Hiroshima and Harlem?">
                What’s the Connection Between Hiroshima and Harlem?                </a>
            </h1>
                            <div class="username">
                    <span class="gkulacki">
                                                <a href="https://allthingsnuclear.org/author/gkulacki" title="Posts by Gregory Kulacki" rel="author">Gregory Kulacki</a><!--
                        --><!--
                            --><span class='mobile-hide'>,</span><span class='mobile-hide'> China project manager and senior analyst</span>
                                            </span><!--
                --></div>
                        <div class="post-date pipe">
                <p><span class="date">June 1, 2020</span> <span class="time">9:25 AM</span> EDT</p>
            </div>
            <div class="article-content">
                <div id="attachment_17449" style="max-width: 1510px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://cdn.allthingsnuclear.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/matsubara-miyoko-property-of-hiroshima-peace-memorial-museum.jpg"><img class="wp-image-17449 size-full" src="https://cdn.allthingsnuclear.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/matsubara-miyoko-property-of-hiroshima-peace-memorial-museum.jpg" alt="" width="1500" height="900" srcset="https://cdn.allthingsnuclear.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/matsubara-miyoko-property-of-hiroshima-peace-memorial-museum.jpg 1500w, https://cdn.allthingsnuclear.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/matsubara-miyoko-property-of-hiroshima-peace-memorial-museum-300x180.jpg 300w, https://cdn.allthingsnuclear.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/matsubara-miyoko-property-of-hiroshima-peace-memorial-museum-768x461.jpg 768w, https://cdn.allthingsnuclear.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/matsubara-miyoko-property-of-hiroshima-peace-memorial-museum-1024x614.jpg 1024w, https://cdn.allthingsnuclear.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/matsubara-miyoko-property-of-hiroshima-peace-memorial-museum-183x110.jpg 183w, https://cdn.allthingsnuclear.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/matsubara-miyoko-property-of-hiroshima-peace-memorial-museum-600x360.jpg 600w" sizes="(max-width: 1500px) 100vw, 1500px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">A drawing depicts a final parting between Miyoko Matsubara, the artist, and her friend Michiko, after both were badly burned during the 1945 bombing of Japan. Matsubara Miyoko, Hiroshima Peace Memorial Museum</p></div>
<p>On June 6, 1964 the American civil-rights activist <a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/codeswitch/2014/06/02/318072652/japanese-american-activist-and-malcolm-x-ally-dies-at-93" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Yuri Kochiyama</a> hosted a group of <a href="https://allthingsnuclear.org/gkulacki/are-there-people-living-in-hiroshima">Japanese hibakusha</a> in her Harlem apartment. The survivors of the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki were on a 150-city <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/1964/04/26/archives/abomb-survivors-begin-world-trip-japanese-on-peace-mission-make-us.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">World Peace Study Mission</a> to <a href="http://wfchiroshima.com/english/about-wfc/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">share their experience</a> of the bomb. Miyoko Matsubara was among them. She was 12 when “<a href="https://web.stanford.edu/class/e297c/war_peace/atomic/hfatman.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Little Boy</a>” exploded over Hiroshima. She <a href="http://205.186.131.100/articles/1999/00/00_matsubara_spirit-hiroshima.php" target="_blank" rel="noopener">described</a> what happened when she regained consciousness after the blast.</p>
<p> <a href="https://allthingsnuclear.org/gkulacki/hiroshima-and-harlem" class="more-link">Read more&nbsp;&gt;</a></p>
                                        <div class="addthis_widget"><a class="addthis_button" addthis:url="https://allthingsnuclear.org/?p=17425" addthis:title="What’s the Connection Between Hiroshima and Harlem?" href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pubid=ra-4dd154a4387f0255"><img src="https://s7.addthis.com/static/btn/sm-share-en.gif" width="83" height="16" alt="Bookmark and Share" style="border:0"/></a></div>            </div>
        </div>

