                --></div>
                        <div class="post-date pipe">
                <p><span class="date">May 18, 2020</span> <span class="time">5:22 PM</span> EDT</p>
            </div>
            <div class="article-content">
                <div id="attachment_17398" style="max-width: 1510px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://cdn.allthingsnuclear.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/extension-vehicle-with-ntelsat-901-satellite.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-17398" src="https://cdn.allthingsnuclear.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/extension-vehicle-with-ntelsat-901-satellite.jpg" alt="" width="1500" height="900" srcset="https://cdn.allthingsnuclear.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/extension-vehicle-with-ntelsat-901-satellite.jpg 1500w, https://cdn.allthingsnuclear.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/extension-vehicle-with-ntelsat-901-satellite-300x180.jpg 300w, https://cdn.allthingsnuclear.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/extension-vehicle-with-ntelsat-901-satellite-768x461.jpg 768w, https://cdn.allthingsnuclear.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/extension-vehicle-with-ntelsat-901-satellite-1024x614.jpg 1024w, https://cdn.allthingsnuclear.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/extension-vehicle-with-ntelsat-901-satellite-183x110.jpg 183w, https://cdn.allthingsnuclear.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/extension-vehicle-with-ntelsat-901-satellite-600x360.jpg 600w" sizes="(max-width: 1500px) 100vw, 1500px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">View of IS-901 satellite from Mission Extension Vehicle-1 (MEV-1) during approach from approximately 20 meters with Earth in the background. The MEV successfully docked with the Intelsat 901 satellite on Tuesday, Feb. 25. Northrop Grumman</p></div>
<p>An updated version of the <a href="https://ucsusa.org/resources/satellite-database">UCS Satellite Database</a>, which includes launches through March 31, 2020, is now available on the UCS website. This update includes the <a href="https://ucsusa.org/sites/default/files/2020-05/changes%20to%20the%20database%204-1-20.pdf">addition to the database of 486 satellites</a> and the removal of 38, for a total of 2,666 active satellites.</p>
<p> <a href="https://allthingsnuclear.org/lgrego/satellite-database-update-more-than-2600-active-satellites-orbiting-the-earth" class="more-link">Read more&nbsp;&gt;</a></p>
                                        <div class="addthis_widget"><a class="addthis_button" addthis:url="https://allthingsnuclear.org/?p=17396" addthis:title="Satellite Database Update: More than 2,600 Active Satellites Orbiting the Earth" href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pubid=ra-4dd154a4387f0255"><img src="https://s7.addthis.com/static/btn/sm-share-en.gif" width="83" height="16" alt="Bookmark and Share" style="border:0"/></a></div>            </div>
        </div>

